	(145,'2016-12-15 09:44:30','2016-12-15 09:44:30','[]','[]','[]','[]',5,'montreal32','NASA finds boron under surface of ancient Mars lake','0.007 SBD',0,'<html>\n<p><img src=\"http://img-s-msn-com.akamaized.net/tenant/amp/entityid/AAlyEYB.img?h=486&amp;w=728&amp;m=6&amp;q=60&amp;o=f&amp;l=f\" width=\"728\" height=\"486\"/>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With the first detection of the boron element on the surface of Mars, researchers are even more hopeful that the red planet has already been habitable. The information was provided by NASA scientists and the Los Alamos National Laboratory during a meeting of the United States Geophysical Union, which took place in San Francisco.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>Boron, an elemental signature of past water that evaporated on Earth, can now be found in arid regions such as Death Valley, located in the Mojave Desert, California. However, with this new finding found by NASA\'s Curiosity rover in the Gale crater on Mars, the idea is that the planet was habitable and had water. However, even if the exact time or era in which this occurred is still unknown, more and more scientists are coming to the conclusion that Mars may have prepared the evolution of microbial life in the last hundreds of thousands of years.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>The Los Alamos laboratory also noted that the temperature, pH, and dissolved mineral in groundwater can make the planet habitable.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>Boron, a very water-soluble element, probably receded with ancient water from the planet to the lake near the exploration area of ​​the Gale crater and subsoil.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>According to the Laboratory, boron was identified by the chemistry and camera instrument (Chemcam), developed in Los Alamos in conjunction with CNES, the French space agency.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>The evaporated water would need to be warm and pH-friendly, says Patrick Gasda, a postdoctoral researcher at the Los Alamos Laboratory in a video. He also states that, according to the boron found, the medium was neither so acid nor so alkaline, and with that normal organisms could have lived there.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>Researchers believe that the Gale crater formed when Mars had water and, as a result, a lake formed inside the crater. Some time later, this lake disappeared and the crater was buried with the sediments.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>The element was found exclusively in the crater because elsewhere boron may be in deeper layers of the planet\'s surface due to sedimentation, or because of chemical changes affecting the element, it has been sedimented elsewhere.</p>\n<p><br></p>\n<p>However, the biggest question on the subject continues in the details on how and why Mars was from a habitable plane</p>\n</html>','{\"tags\":[\"marte\"],\"image\":[\"http://img-s-msn-com.akamaized.net/tenant/amp/entityid/AAlyEYB.img?h=486&w=728&m=6&q=60&o=f&l=f\"],\"app\":\"steemit/0.1\",\"format\":\"html\"}','steem','[\"montreal32\",\"herverisson\",\"drac59\",\"smysullivan\",\"friendly\"]','nasa-finds-boron-under-surface-of-ancient-mars-lake','SBD','marte'),
