	(174,'2016-12-15 16:32:45','2016-12-15 15:50:30','biology','brain','news','[]',42,'krnel','Bigger Brains - Bigger Burden or Bigger Benefit? New Study Has Answers','20.144 SBD',0,'### Bigger brains are a good thing for all animals, as they tend to live longer. \n\n#### But, previous research has suggested one disadvantage in terms of survival that is also reflected in humans, and that is of a reduction in reproduction and the amount of offspring produced. Taking this into consideration, bigger brains are not so smart, despite the longer life correlation.\n\n<center><img src=\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/reddeer-6227076309_9e91d6d676_z2d2cd.jpg\" alt=\"reddeer-6227076309_9e91d6d676_z2d2cd.jpg\" border=\"0\"><br/><em><a href=\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/27770620@N02/6227076309\">source</a></em></center>\n\n### A new study about red deer in the UK, says differently. \n\nMeasuring the interior volume of 1314 red deer skulls from a population that has been studied for over 40 years, they did not find any actual correlation between a red deer female\'s brain size, and how often she gave birth in her life.\n\n<center><img src=\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/red-deer-skullsbe3ef.jpg\" alt=\"red-deer-skullsbe3ef.jpg\" border=\"0\"><br/><em><a href=\"\">source</a></em></center>\n\nThis was reported in the Royal Society Open Science journal, published yesterday, December 14th. The publication title is [Endocranial volume is heritable and is associated with longevity and fitness in a wild mammal](http://rsos.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/3/12/160622). Read it in full in the link.\n\n<center><img src=\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/bigger-brain32523.jpg\" alt=\"bigger-brain32523.jpg\" border=\"0\"><br/><em><a href=\"https://www.newscientist.com/article/2115791-first-evidence-that-wild-mammals-benefit-from-bigger-brains/\">source</a></em></center>\n\nAdditionally, the red deer females with larger brains were found to not only have longer lives, but also having more surviving offspring (not that they gave birth more or less), passing their bigger brains onto evolutionary success. Therefore, the bigger brains are beneficial and a success in the long term. Red deer males, however, did not have any association between the size of their brains and longevity or their lifetime breeding success. The scientists noted that the male red deers do have antlers, which could account for differences in brains.\n\n<div class=\"pull-right\"><center><img src=\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/14/350px-ComparitiveBrainSize3f4b6.jpg\" alt=\"350px-ComparitiveBrainSize3f4b6.jpg\" border=\"0\"><br/><em><a href=\"http://en.citizendium.org/wiki/Brain_size\">source</a></em></center></div>\n\nAll in all bigger brains aren\'t such a burden, despite previous research on guppies or other animals showing larger brains requiring more energy to help improve learning, but resulting in fewer offspring. \n\nThe red deer shows this is not the case for all animals. Larger brains aren\'t as costly as was previously thought.\n\n**Brains are a gift**. Brain power comes with brain size in most animal species. We can be thankful we have a well developed brain to give us the power of consciousness we have. Even if our brain isn\'t technically the largest. :D\n\n---\n#### Thank you for your time and attention! I appreciate the knowledge reaching more people. Take care. Peace.\n\n<h6><em>Want to talk about Steemit or philosophical topics? Join me on [Steemit Community Discussions](https://discord.gg/bJCnv5j).</em></h6>\n\n---\nReferences:\n- [Endocranial volume is heritable and is associated with longevity and fitness in a wild mammal](http://rsos.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/3/12/160622)\n- [First evidence that wild mammals benefit from bigger brains](https://www.newscientist.com/article/2115791-first-evidence-that-wild-mammals-benefit-from-bigger-brains/)\n\n---\n##### If you appreciate and value the content, please consider: \n<center>Upvoting, Sharing, and Resteeming below.</center>\n\n[![Follow](https://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/08/30/follow2be5e.png)](https://steemit.com/@krnel) me for more content to come!\n\n---\n@krnel\n2016-12-15, 10:50am','{\"tags\":[\"science\",\"animals\",\"brain\",\"news\"],\"users\":[\"krnel\"],\"image\":[\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/reddeer-6227076309_9e91d6d676_z2d2cd.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/red-deer-skullsbe3ef.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/bigger-brain32523.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/14/350px-ComparitiveBrainSize3f4b6.jpg\",\"https://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/08/30/follow2be5e.png\"],\"links\":[\"https://www.flickr.com/photos/27770620@N02/6227076309\",\"http://rsos.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/3/12/160622\",\"https://www.newscientist.com/article/2115791-first-evidence-that-wild-mammals-benefit-from-bigger-brains/\",\"http://en.citizendium.org/wiki/Brain_size\",\"https://discord.gg/bJCnv5j\",\"https://steemit.com/@krnel\"],\"app\":\"steemit/0.1\",\"format\":\"markdown\"}','steem','[\"krnel\",\"cryptofunk\",\"bottymcbotface\",\"teamsteem\",\"proctologic\",\"proctologic2\",\"proctologic3\",\"lovethepeople\",\"porco-bastardo\",\"adelja\",\"murh\",\"chappers\",\"nanzo-scoop\",\"nanzo-scoop\",\"nanzo-scoop\",\"yoonjang0707\",\"blocho\",\"sanghkaang\",\"nanzo-scoop\",\"immortalfame\",\"jyp\",\"mokluc\",\"selwi\",\"koskl\",\"velourex\",\"makishart\",\"leesunmoo\",\"jsg\",\"ksc\",\"kyusho\",\"hr1\",\"immortalfame\",\"jyp\",\"strangerarray\",\"nxtblg\",\"summonerrk\",\"mokluc\",\"selwi\",\"koskl\",\"velourex\",\"makishart\",\"leesunmoo\"]','bigger-brains-bigger-burden-or-bigger-benefit-new-study-has-answers','SBD','science'),
	(175,'2016-12-15 15:46:39','2016-12-15 15:46:39','healthy','life','recipes','shrimp',12,'blueorgy','? Spicy Shrimp & ? Bucatini Pasta with ? Kale',NULL,0,'I\'m back again with another meal I prepared just the other night using two of my favorites as of late **Shrimp** & **Kale** (favorite of @heiditravels so I\'ve learned) and although I have been seriously cutting one of my all time favorites **Pasta** out of my dishes lately I couldn\'t resist this recipe... so I went for it. Again this recipe is from Blue Apron and is not mine own (Still a little shy with my own creations but I promise I will be sharing soon) If you are here to follow along and learn some culinary skills I hope you enjoy the end result and cooking with me. \n\n<h1>http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1099f9eca.jpg</h1>\n\n**RELAXATION**\nAlways remember that cooking can be a form of meditation, relaxation, and centering one self through the simple movements the culinary experience (have fun) . Don\'t rush and take your time (if possible) and enjoy your learning experience. I tend to cut and prepare everything ahead of time and clear the cooking space making it much less stressful.\n\n**MUSIC**\nThis is defiantly a personal thing and I\'m sure for some that includes have no distractions and no music at all but for me I enjoy classical music mostly when cooking and the occasional chill downtempo music selection. \n\n**THE MEAL**\nTonight’s meal is inspired by classic Italian-American recipes for shrimp scampi, which popularly combines shrimp and pasta. For especially dynamic results, we’re using garlic in two ways. First, we’re cooking some with kale and a bit of water to bring out a well-rounded sweetness. Then, we’re sautéing more garlic with plump shrimp in a bit of butter, where it takes on a flavorful piquancy that mirrors the spicy red pepper flakes in the dish.\n\nCOOK TIME | MAKES | NUTRITION\n-- | -- | --\n15-25mins | 2 Servings | Est. 790 calories\n\n**INGREDIENTS**\n10 Ounces Shrimp\n½ Pound Bucatini Pasta\n3 Cloves Garlic\n2 Scallions\n1 Bunch Kale\n1 Lemon\n2 Tablespoons Butter\n¼ Teaspoon Crushed Red Pepper Flakes\n\n<hr>\n\n**1. Prepare the ingredients:**\nWash and dry the fresh produce. Heat a large pot of salted water to boiling on high. Cut off and discard the root ends of the scallions; thinly slice, separating the white bottoms and green tops. Peel and mince the garlic. Remove and discard the kale stems; finely chop the leaves. Quarter and deseed the lemon.\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1079c6e79.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_108098604.jpg\n\n<hr>\n\n**2. Cook the kale:**\nIn a large pan (nonstick, if you have one), heat 2 teaspoons of olive oil on medium until hot. Add the white bottoms of the scallions and half the garlic; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, 30 seconds to 1 minute, or until fragrant. Add the kale; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, 1 to 2 minutes, or until slightly wilted. Add ¼ cup of water; cook, stirring occasionally, 4 to 6 minutes, or until the kale has wilted and the water has cooked off. Turn off the heat and stir in the juice of 2 lemon wedges. Transfer to a bowl; season with salt and pepper to taste. Wipe out the pan.\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1083d9947.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1086abad9.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1087acb89.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_108894d50.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1092832ab.jpg\n\n<hr>\n\n**3. Cook the pasta:**\nWhile the kale cooks, add the pasta to the pot of boiling water. Cook 8 to 10 minutes, or until al dente (still slightly firm to the bite). Reserving ¾ cup of the pasta cooking water, drain thoroughly.\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_10897b557.jpg\n\n<hr>\n\n**4 Start the shrimp:**\nPat the shrimp dry with paper towels; season with salt and pepper. In the same pan, heat 2 teaspoons of olive oil on medium-high until hot. Add the seasoned shrimp in a single, even layer and cook 1 to 2 minutes on the first side, or until lightly browned.\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_10813fe24.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1082dc68f.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_109058322.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_109152ea8.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1093d0636.jpg\n\n<hr>\n\n**5 Finish the shrimp:**\nFlip the shrimp. To the pan, add the butter, cooked kale, remaining garlic and as much of the red pepper flakes as you’d like, depending on how spicy you’d like the dish to be; season with salt and pepper. Cook, stirring frequently, 2 to 3 minutes, or until thoroughly combined and the shrimp are cooked through.\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1094c67a3.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1095ca6e0.jpg\n\n<hr>\n\n**6 Finish & plate your dish:**\nAdd the cooked pasta and half the reserved pasta cooking water to the pan. Cook, stirring vigorously to coat the pasta, 1 to 2 minutes, or until well combined and heated through. (If the sauce seems dry, gradually add the remaining pasta cooking water to achieve your desired consistency.) Remove from heat and season with salt and pepper to taste. Divide the finished shrimp and pasta between 2 dishes. Garnish with the green tops of the scallions and a drizzle of olive oil. Serve with the remaining lemon wedges on the side, if you’d like. Enjoy!\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_10966885f.jpg\n\nhttp://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1099f9eca.jpg\n\n<hr>\n\n<h1>*Bon Appétit\nblue*</h1>','{\"tags\":[\"food\",\"healthy\",\"life\",\"recipes\",\"shrimp\"],\"users\":[\"heiditravels\"],\"image\":[\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1099f9eca.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1079c6e79.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_108098604.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1083d9947.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1086abad9.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1087acb89.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_108894d50.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1092832ab.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_10897b557.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_10813fe24.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1082dc68f.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_109058322.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_109152ea8.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1093d0636.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1094c67a3.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_1095ca6e0.jpg\",\"http://www.steemimg.com/images/2016/12/15/IMG_10966885f.jpg\"],\"app\":\"steemit/0.1\",\"format\":\"markdown\"}','steem','[\"blueorgy\",\"adelja\",\"olezoom\",\"gidlark\",\"sompitonov\",\"wang\",\"steemaccess\",\"murh\",\"blocho\",\"shredlord\",\"funnyman\",\"funnyman\"]','spicy-shrimp-and-bucatini-pasta-with-kale','SBD','food'),
